<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-10-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-10-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="225" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Conger</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-10-12"><hi rend="italic">October 12,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Conger reports that the merchants of all nationalities request
                            postponement for six months of enforcement of trade-mark regulations.
                            German and French ministers, in accordance with instructions, strongly
                            demand postponement. The British minister will not object. The majority
                            of the merchants wish no regulations whatever.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>